    900          /***************************************************************************//**
    901           * @brief
    902           *   Enter energy mode 2 (EM2).
    903           *
    904           * @details
    905           *   When entering EM2, high-frequency clocks are disabled, i.e., HFXO, HFRCO
    906           *   and AUXHFRCO (for AUXHFRCO, see exception note below). When re-entering
    907           *   EM0, HFRCO is re-enabled and the core will be clocked by the configured
    908           *   HFRCO band. This ensures a quick wakeup from EM2.
    909           *
    910           *   However, prior to entering EM2, the core may have been using another
    911           *   oscillator than HFRCO. The @p restore parameter gives the user the option
    912           *   to restore all HF oscillators according to state prior to entering EM2,
    913           *   as well as the clock used to clock the core. This restore procedure is
    914           *   handled by SW. However, since handled by SW, it will not be restored
    915           *   before completing the interrupt function(s) waking up the core!
    916           *
    917           * @note
    918           *   If restoring core clock to use the HFXO oscillator, which has been
    919           *   disabled during EM2 mode, this function will stall until the oscillator
    920           *   has stabilized. Stalling time can be reduced by adding interrupt
    921           *   support detecting stable oscillator, and an asynchronous switch to the
    922           *   original oscillator. See CMU documentation. Such a feature is however
    923           *   outside the scope of the implementation in this function.
    924           * @note
    925           *   If ERRATA_FIX_EMU_E110_ENABLE is active, the core's SLEEPONEXIT feature
    926           *   can not be used.
    927           * @note
    928           *   This function is incompatible with the Power Manager module. When the
    929           *   Power Manager module is present, it must be the one deciding at which
    930           *   EM level the device sleeps to ensure the application properly works. Using
    931           *   both at the same time could lead to undefined behavior in the application.
    932           * @par
    933           *   If HFXO is re-enabled by this function, and NOT used to clock the core,
    934           *   this function will not wait for HFXO to stabilize. This must be considered
    935           *   by the application if trying to use features relying on that oscillator
    936           *   upon return.
    937           * @par
    938           *   If a debugger is attached, the AUXHFRCO will not be disabled if enabled
    939           *   upon entering EM2. It will thus remain enabled when returning to EM0
    940           *   regardless of the @p restore parameter.
    941           * @par
    942           *   If HFXO autostart and select is enabled by using CMU_HFXOAutostartEnable(),
    943           *   the automatic starting and selecting of the core clocks will be done,
    944           *   regardless of the @p restore parameter, when waking up on the wakeup
    945           *   sources corresponding to the autostart and select setting.
    946           * @par
    947           *   If voltage scaling is supported, the restore parameter is true and the EM0
    948           *   voltage scaling level is set higher than the EM2 level, then the EM0 level is
    949           *   also restored.
    950           * @par
    951           *   On Series 2 Config 2 devices (EFRxG22), this function will also relock the
    952           *   DPLL if the DPLL is used and @p restore is true.
    953           *
    954           *   Note that the hardware will automatically update the HFRCO frequency in the
    955           *   case where voltage scaling is used in EM2/EM3 and not in EM0/EM1. When the
    956           *   restore argument to this function is true then software will restore the
    957           *   original HFRCO frequency after EM2/EM3 wake up. If the restore argument is
    958           *   false then the HFRCO frequency is 19 MHz when coming out of EM2/EM3 and
    959           *   all wait states are at a safe value.
    960           *
    961           * @param[in] restore
    962           *   @li true - save and restore oscillators, clocks and voltage scaling, see
    963           *   function details.
    964           *   @li false - do not save and restore oscillators and clocks, see function
    965           *   details.
    966           * @par
    967           *   The @p restore option should only be used if all clock control is done
    968           *   via the CMU API.
    969           ******************************************************************************/

