   1112          /***************************************************************************//**
   1113           * @brief
   1114           *   Enter energy mode 3 (EM3).
   1115           *
   1116           * @details
   1117           *   When entering EM3, the high-frequency clocks are disabled by hardware, i.e., HFXO,
   1118           *   HFRCO, and AUXHFRCO (for AUXHFRCO, see exception note below). In addition,
   1119           *   the low-frequency clocks, i.e., LFXO and LFRCO are disabled by software. When
   1120           *   re-entering EM0, HFRCO is re-enabled and the core will be clocked by the
   1121           *   configured HFRCO band. This ensures a quick wakeup from EM3.
   1122           *
   1123           *   However, prior to entering EM3, the core may have been using an
   1124           *   oscillator other than HFRCO. The @p restore parameter gives the user the option
   1125           *   to restore all HF/LF oscillators according to state prior to entering EM3,
   1126           *   as well as the clock used to clock the core. This restore procedure is
   1127           *   handled by software. However, since it is handled by software, it will not be restored
   1128           *   before completing the interrupt function(s) waking up the core!
   1129           *
   1130           * @note
   1131           *   If restoring core clock to use an oscillator other than HFRCO, this
   1132           *   function will stall until the oscillator has stabilized. Stalling time
   1133           *   can be reduced by adding interrupt support detecting stable oscillator,
   1134           *   and an asynchronous switch to the original oscillator. See CMU
   1135           *   documentation. This feature is, however, outside the scope of the
   1136           *   implementation in this function.
   1137           * @note
